</tr>

<tr>

<td>ISO 10993</td>

<td>Biological Evaluation</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>IEC 62304</td>

<td>Medical Device Software</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>IEC 60601</td>

<td>Electrical Medical Equipment</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>ISO 15223-1</td>

<td>Medical Device Symbols</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>ISO 20417</td>

<td>Information Supplied by Manufacturer</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h2>Typical Documents Required</h2>

<ul>

<li>Quality Manual</li>

<li>Quality Policy</li>

<li>Quality Objectives</li>

<li>Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs)</li>

<li>Device Master File (DMF)</li>

<li>Risk Management File</li>

<li>Design History File (DHF)</li>

<li>Validation Protocols</li>

<li>Complaint Handling Procedure</li>

<li>CAPA Records</li>

<li>Internal Audit Reports</li>

<li>Management Review Minutes</li>

<li>Training Records</li>

<li>Supplier Qualification Records</li>

<li>Post Market Surveillance Reports</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h2>Practical Example</h2>

<p>

Suppose a company manufactures Total Hip Replacement implants.

ISO 13485 requires the organization to maintain controlled procedures
for design, purchasing, manufacturing, sterilization, packaging,
complaint handling, traceability, PMS activities and CAPA.

During certification audits, auditors verify that every activity is
documented and controlled according to the Quality Management System.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

